<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="451" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,582,1444,1470]" box="[151,582,1444,1470]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,582,1444,1470]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="10" pageNumber="451" reason="1">
<taxonomicName authority="Omer-Cooper" authorityName="Omer-Cooper" box="[151,582,1444,1470]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Canthyporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="451" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brincki">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,582,1444,1470]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,401,1444,1470]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="451">Canthyporus brincki</emphasis>
Omer-Cooper
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,1514,1863]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451">
Still only known from the 
<typeStatus box="[456,504,1515,1539]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451">type</typeStatus>
locality, from Quthing in what is now 
<collectingCountry box="[953,1047,1514,1539]" name="Lesotho" pageId="10" pageNumber="451">Lesotho</collectingCountry>
. I have re-examined the 
<typeStatus box="[1331,1432,1514,1539]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451">holotype</typeStatus>
, deposited in 
<collectionCode box="[293,375,1551,1574]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451">LUMZ</collectionCode>
, and illustrate the habitus and male genitalia here for comparison (see 
<figureCitation box="[1158,1234,1550,1575]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1636,1658]" captionTargetBox="[157,1416,200,1595]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,195,1612]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Canthyporus exilis group, male habitus. A) C. aenigmaticus; B) C. brincki holotype; C) C. exilis; D) C. namaqualacrimus sp. nov. holotype; E) C. nebulosus; F) C. pallidus sp. nov. holotype. Scale bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/238992/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="451">
Figs. 
<number box="[1220,1234,1551,1575]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
&amp; 
<figureCitation box="[1268,1285,1551,1575]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1743,1765]" captionTargetBox="[171,1425,362,1706]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,337,1721]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Canthyporus exilis group, male genitalia (ventral and lateral view of median lobe of aedeagus, plus right paramere). A) C. aenigmaticus; B) C. brincki holotype; C) C. exilis; D) C. namaqualacrimus sp. nov. holotype; E) C. nebulosus; F) C. pallidus sp. nov. holotype. Scale bar = 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/238993/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="451">
<number box="[1268,1285,1551,1575]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
). The species is closest to 
<taxonomicName box="[288,433,1587,1611]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Canthyporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="451" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nebulosus">
<emphasis box="[288,433,1587,1611]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="451">C. nebulosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[487,609,1587,1611]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Canthyporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="451" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallidus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[487,609,1587,1611]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="451">C. pallidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[617,706,1586,1611]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[617,706,1586,1611]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, and is best distinguished by a combination of colour pattern and male genitalia—see key below. In her description, 
<bibRefCitation author="Omer-Cooper" box="[751,992,1622,1647]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451" refString="Omer-Cooper, J. (1965) Coleoptera: Dytiscidae. A review of the Dytiscidae of Southern Africa being the results of the Lund University Expedition 1950 - 1951, with which are incorporated all other records known to the author. In: South African Animal Life, 11, 59 - 214." type="journal article" year="1965">
Omer-Cooper (
<number box="[926,984,1622,1647]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451" value="1965.0">1965</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
states that the 
<typeStatus box="[1177,1275,1622,1647]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451">holotype</typeStatus>
was taken in locality 
<number box="[245,287,1659,1683]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451" value="230.0">230</number>
of the Swedish South African Expedition on 
<date box="[819,934,1658,1683]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451" value="1951-03-11">
<number box="[819,844,1658,1683]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451" value="11.0">11</number>
/ 
<number box="[854,867,1658,1683]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451" value="3.0">3</number>
/ 
<number box="[876,934,1658,1683]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451" value="1951.0">1951</number>
</date>
, which is listed as “Quthing, at light in the evening… 
<quantity box="[265,352,1694,1719]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.70688" pageId="10" pageNumber="451" unit="ft" value="5600.0">5600 ft</quantity>
.” in 
<bibRefCitation author="Brinck" box="[403,712,1694,1719]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451" refString="Brinck, P. &amp; Rudebeck, G. (1955) List of localities investigated by the Swedish Expedition to South Africa in 1950 - 1951. In: Hanstrom, B., Brinck, P. &amp; Rudebeck, G. (Eds.) South African Animal Life, 1, 62 - 100" type="journal article" year="1955">
Brinck &amp; Rudebeck (
<number box="[642,703,1694,1719]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451" value="1955.0">1955</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. A study of the label data of the 
<typeStatus box="[1075,1173,1694,1719]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451">holotype</typeStatus>
reveals instead that the specimen was taken at locality 
<number box="[510,552,1731,1755]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451" value="234.0">234</number>
on 
<date box="[598,715,1730,1755]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451" value="1951-03-15">
<number box="[598,625,1730,1755]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451" value="15.0">15</number>
/ 
<number box="[635,648,1730,1755]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451" value="3.0">3</number>
/ 
<number box="[657,715,1730,1755]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451" value="1951.0">1951</number>
</date>
, as noted by 
<bibRefCitation author="Bistrom" box="[868,1171,1730,1755]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451" refString="Bistrom, O. &amp; Nilsson, A. N. (2006) Taxonomic revision of the Ethiopian genus Canthyporus (Coleoptera Dytiscidae). Memorie della Societa Entomologica Italiana, 85, 209 - 306. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.4081 / memorieSEI. 2006.209" type="journal article" year="2006">
Biström &amp; Nilsson (
<number box="[1101,1163,1730,1755]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451" value="2006.0">2006</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. 
<collectingCountry box="[1184,1215,1731,1755]" name="American Samoa" pageId="10" pageNumber="451">As</collectingCountry>
stated in 
<bibRefCitation author="Brinck" pageId="10" pageNumber="451" refString="Brinck, P. &amp; Rudebeck, G. (1955) List of localities investigated by the Swedish Expedition to South Africa in 1950 - 1951. In: Hanstrom, B., Brinck, P. &amp; Rudebeck, G. (Eds.) South African Animal Life, 1, 62 - 100" type="journal article" year="1955">
Brinck &amp; Rudebeck (
<number box="[278,338,1766,1791]" pageId="10" pageNumber="451" value="1955.0">1955</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, this locality contained a range of sampled habitats, including a forested stream, a stream flowing through a valley with steep rock walls, with a wet and shaded wall covered by algae. Given the habitat preferences of other members of the 
<taxonomicName box="[427,486,1838,1862]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Canthyporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="451" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exilis">
<emphasis box="[427,486,1838,1862]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="451">exilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group it seems likely that the specimen was obtained from one of these habitats.
</paragraph>
